## Transitions

<!-- awf:section transitions -->
- `Proposed → Accepted` freezes the body and establishes the content digest without applying operations.
- `Proposed|Accepted → Implementing` appends the status event then a first Applied batch, together with its claim mutations.
- `Implementing → Implementing` appends exactly one middle Applied batch with its mutations.
- `Implementing → Implemented` appends the final Applied batch then the terminal status event with its mutations.
- `Proposed|Accepted → Implemented` remains the direct one-transaction path for all operations; `None.` and one-operation ADRs use it.
- `Proposed|Accepted|Implementing → Abandoned` appends only the terminal status and rationale. Already Applied operations remain authoritative; Remaining operations become Canceled.

`Implemented` and `Abandoned` are terminal. There is no `Superseded` status: an ADR is never active authority, so a later decision changes the affected current-state claims through its own State changes rather than superseding this ADR.
<!-- awf:end -->

## State changes and the claim handshake

<!-- awf:section state-changes -->
An ADR's `## State changes` section is the authoritative link to the topics it governs: either `None.` or a list of `- add`, `- update`, and `- remove` entries, each naming one claim by its qualified `<domain>/<topic>:<slug>` id.

- **At `Accepted`** the operations are frozen instruction. Every operation's destination topic metadata must already exist (an empty topic shell for a pending `add`). The claims describing current reality are unchanged; a pending operation surfaces only as a bounded Accepted notice in `awf context`.
- **At `Implementing`** each Applied event and exactly its matching claim mutations form one checked Git pair. An `add` appears with this ADR as Origin; an `update` preserves Origin and the prior Revised-by prefix, then appends this ADR; a `remove` disappears. Remaining operations continue to appear as pending progress.
- **At `Implemented`** all declarations are Applied. A direct transition uses one implicit batch; an incremental transition appends its final batch before the status event.
- **At `Abandoned`** Applied operations and their provenance remain historical facts, while Remaining operations become Canceled and authorize nothing.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Procedure

Pick the status transition, then:

<!-- awf:section procedure-status-edit -->
1. **Edit the ADR history and status.** For a first incremental batch, append Implementing status then an Applied event; for a middle batch append one Applied event without changing status; for the final batch append Applied then Implemented status; for abandonment append only Abandoned with a rationale. Applied grammar is `- YYYY-MM-DD: Applied; state-sequence: <n>; operations: <operation-list>`. Repeat the frozen digest on status events and use the next sequence `awf check` reports.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-claim-mutation -->
2. **Apply exactly the batch's State changes.** Stage the matching add/update/remove edits under `.awf/topics/parts/<domain>/<topic>/current-state.md` in the same commit as the Applied event. Never apply Remaining or Canceled operations. On abandonment preserve claims authorized by earlier Applied events.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section state-doc-update -->
3. **Update any current-state topic** whose claims this ADR moves: the claim edits above are that update. Refresh the surrounding explanatory prose in the same topic part when the domain's position has shifted, in the same commit. Do not hand-maintain a per-domain decisions index; the generated domain doc links the topic list instead.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-regen -->
4. **Regenerate INDEX.md.** Run `{{ with .vars.activeMdRegenCmd }}{{ . }}{{ else }}awf sync{{ end }}` to regenerate `{{ .layout.indexMd }}`. Stage the result. Do not hand-edit `INDEX.md`; always regenerate and commit it alongside any ADR status change.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section procedure-gate -->
5. **Validate the staged transaction.** Stage the complete transaction, run `awf check --staged`, then run {{ with .vars.gateCmd }}`{{ . }}`{{ else }}the project's gate{{ end }}. Commit only after both commands pass. The hook repeats the staged check as defense in depth. If either command fails, fix the cause and re-stage before retrying.
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section commit-templates -->
## Commit subject templates

Use these subjects for each transition type:

- `docs(adr): accept NNNN <short title>` for `Proposed → Accepted`
- `<feat|fix|refactor>(<scope>): <subject> (applies NNNN batch)` for first or middle Applied batches
- `<feat|fix|refactor>(<scope>): <subject> (implements NNNN)` for a direct or final batch
- `docs(adr): abandon NNNN <short title>` for any legal transition to Abandoned
<!-- awf:end -->

<!-- awf:section amendment-while-proposed -->
## Amendment-while-Proposed

While `status: Proposed`, all sections may be amended freely as edge cases or scope refinements surface. Two flavours:

- **Plain amendment.** Edit the relevant section; commit with `docs(adr): amend Context for <title>` or fold into a co-located implementation commit when the change is small.
- **Deferral.** When scope shrinks mid-flight, amend the still-`Proposed` ADR's Context with what was deferred and why; commit as `docs(adr): amend NNNN, defer <part>; <reason>`. Deferral is a Context edit on a `Proposed` ADR, not a lifecycle state; deferred work lands in a follow-up ADR or the roadmap.

Once `Accepted` or `Implemented`, the body's meaning is frozen; a schema retrofit may migrate its machine-readable encoding. Only the `status` field and the append-only `## Status history` are editable in place.
<!-- awf:end -->

## Notes

<!-- awf:section notes -->
- **Authoritative source:** `{{ .layout.workflowRef }}` and `{{ .layout.adrDir }}/README.md`. This skill is a procedural pointer, not a contract restatement.
- **Append-only rule:** once any live state is reached, only the `status` field and the append-only `## Status history` are editable in place. The body is the historical record: its meaning is frozen, and append-only protects rationale, not bookkeeping - a meaning-preserving schema retrofit may migrate its machine-readable encoding.
- **`{{ .layout.indexMd }}` is auto-generated** by `{{ with .vars.activeMdRegenCmd }}{{ . }}{{ else }}awf sync{{ end }}` and is **never hand-edited**. Always regenerate and commit it alongside any ADR status change.
- Does not commit on your behalf; surfaces the right edits for you to land.
<!-- awf:end -->
